The origin for these discrepancies can come from the fact that the simulations take into account only DM, while the properties of galaxies are also influenced by the presence of baryons. The newest hydrodynamical simulations obtained by many independent groups have shown that baryonic feedback can in fact soften the inner cusps in the profile and generate core-like profiles like the ones observed for dwarf galaxies. The main effects are supernova feedback flattening and dynamical friction from baryonic clumps (for a more detailed list of these and other baryonic processes, see (Del Popolo and Le Delliou 2017)). These simulations show a threshold mass of Mvir∼1010M⊙\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$M_{\mathrm {vir}}\sim 10^{10}\, M_\odot $$\end{document} below which the simulation predict profiles that are cusped (Governato et al. 2012; Munshi et al. 2013; Madau et al. 2014; Oñorbe et al. 2015; Tollet et al. 2016; Fitts et al. 2017).

