DES and future observations are expected to discover more of those ultra-faint galaxies, which can alleviate this discrepancy, but there is still a debate if this will solve the problem. Another possibility is that low-mass subhalos are there, but we just cannot see them since they have very low baryonic content. One can expect that for low mass subhalos, galaxy formation is suppressed since the photoionizing background heats the gas, reducing its cooling rate and inhibiting gas accretion for Mvir∼109M⊙\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
