				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} 10^{-25}\, \mathrm {eV} \lesssim m \lesssim 2 \, \mathrm {eV}\,. \end{aligned}$$\end{document}The lower bound on the mass is very general and comes from the fact that the size of the condensate core cannot be larger than the halo, since we want the condensate only on galactic scales and normal DM on larger scales. The maximum case we can have for the formation of a condensate is where the de Broglie wavelength of the ULDM particle is of the order of the size of the halo. Taking this bound at virialization, there is a maximum value on how large the de Broglie wavelength can be λdB<R200\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
