				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$z=100$$\end{document} until today. The authors found from the simulation that, in SIFDM model, the growth of structure proceeds less efficiently than in CDM, as expected for the ULDM models, although more efficiently than expected, with the suppression more pronounced on small-scales and at high temperatures. They also study the role of the interaction strength and of the equation of state.

In the case of fuzzy DM, where we have a (non-interacting) ultra-light scalar field in FRW universe, the field can behave as dark matter, early dark energy or dark energy depending on the mass of this field. The behaviour of the field depends on how its mass is related to the Hubble parameter. At early times, the ultra-light field has m≪H\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ m \ll H$$\end{document}. In this regime, the field is almost frozen and behaves as DE with w≈-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$w \approx -1$$\end{document}. As m∼3H\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m \sim 3 H$$\end{document}, the field starts to coherently oscillate around the potential minimum and to behave as DM, where the equations of state averaged over the oscillations approaches zero. Depending on the mass, the oscillating DM phase can happen at different times of the evolution of the universe.

If the oscillating phase happens after radiation-matter domination, the ultra-light field behaves like DM. From Hložek et al. (2015), we see this happens for m≳10-27eV\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m \gtrsim 10^{-27} \, \mathrm {eV}$$\end{document}. This bound comes from observations from the CMB and LSS galaxy clustering, and in this regime the ultra-light field can oscillates before the present day and the field redshifts as DM. More generally, for m≲10-32eV\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m \lesssim 10^{-32} \, \mathrm {eV}$$\end{document} we can still have the ultra-light field behaving as DM, since the field starts oscillating before the present time, but in this case the ultra-light field can only make a fraction of the DM.

For m∼10-33eV≈H0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m \sim 10^{-33} \, \mathrm {eV} \approx H_0$$\end{document}, the field behaves like a quintessence field, if in the presence of a potential, and it can be the responsible for the late time acceleration. Since the field is virtually frozen until the present time, or slowly-rolling the potential, with almost constant density, and it behaves very closely to a cosmological constant. With observations from CMB, we can see that in this case the ultra-light fields have a maximum bound on the energy density compatible with the expected amount of DE in the universe. For masses around 10-32eV≲m≲10-27eV\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$10^{-32} \, \mathrm {eV} \lesssim m \lesssim 10^{-27} \, \mathrm {eV}$$\end{document}, the ultra-light field behaves like DE earlier than what it is expected, and can be thought as an early DE component.

In the previous case and in the case of quintessence, a ultra-light field is a component with a very small mass m≈3H0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m \approx 3 H_0$$\end{document}, that dominates around the present times and drives the acceleration. Differently, in the framework we present here, the dark sector is composed only by DM described by a superfluid, without DE. The late acceleration emerges from the dynamics of this superfluid, and we have a unified model for the behaviour of DM and DE. We can see how this arises from the model described below.

In this entire section, we are using the same formalism as the one defined for the DM superfluid (and the EFT of superfluids from Sect. 3.4. In the model we present here, we assume that the superfluid is composed by two different species, which can be represented by the ground (Ψ1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
